  "text": "To assess a potential influence of HIV infection on HBsAg levels, we compared HBsAg levels in 46 HIV/HBV co-infected patients not receiving anti-HBV therapy with 46 HBV monoinfected untreated individuals matched for age, sex, HBeAg status and HBV DNA concentration, which are considered the most relevant factors associated with HBsAg concentrations [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ( Table 2 ). HBsAg levels were higher in HIV/HBV co-infected patients vs. HBV mono-infected patients (4.29 vs 3.94 log10 IU/ mL, P = 0.016) despite similar HBV DNA concentration (Fig. 4a) . Thus, HBsAg productivity (HBsAg/HBV-DNA ratio) was significantly higher in patients with HIV/HBV co-infection (0.83 vs 0.63, P = 0.008, Fig. 4b ).",
